abstract = {Personalized learning research suggests that personalization may be a promising strategy for offering K-12 and Higher Education students a sense of ownership over their learning process. Studies demonstrate that personalized learning may support students’ development of new skillsets as well as scaffold lifelong learning practices, reduce time spent on learning, and mitigate information overload.&nbsp;While the research in K-12 and Higher Education is promising, research into personalized learning&nbsp;strategies&nbsp;in Workforce Training and Development Programs has been somewhat limited.&nbsp;Additionally, a literature review revealed that definitions and implementations of personalized learning vary in regard to&nbsp;what is being personalized (distribution channel, interface, content, functionality), who conducts the personalization (user,&nbsp;system, blended format), how the&nbsp;(user,&nbsp;system, blended format)&nbsp;personalizes, and&nbsp;the type of learner data collected.&nbsp;This research sought expert feedback in identifying the variables, characterizations, priorities, and applications of personalized learning in Workforce Training and Development Programs.&nbsp;Three rounds of Delphi Feedback indicated that experts conceive of personalized learning as a learner-centered strategy driven by content and social interactions and underpinned by an ethos of flexibility and learner choice.&nbsp;A 5 Level Personalized Learning Interaction Framework (PLiF) building upon Moore's Theory of Interaction is proposed to structure personalized learning for Workforce Training and Development Programs.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;},
