abstract = {The evaluation of academic performance is getting an increasing interest among researchers in the field of education. From the beginning, several international organizations were interested in measuring academic performance with the aim of improving educational policies and practices to increase school effectiveness. One of the organizations that is strongly committed and that has studies for the evaluation of academic performance is the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), with the Program for International Student Assessment (PISA). This program has great international relevance as it establishes the primary objective of studying and evaluating the acquisition of skills in 15-year-old students, a result that is taken into account by the different countries to modify their educational policies. This is the case of Portugal, a country that aims to improve the skills of its students by reforming curriculum policies. Now, a key question in these changes is to check the PISA variables that are directly related to the curriculum to know to what extent these variables can be used to improve school effectiveness, in order to predict the success of the political changes that are implemented in Portugal. For this purpose, a first quantitative study is carried out, which aims to analyze the impact of the variables (students, schools, and curriculum) on the competences presented by students, resulting from there, their relationship with the level of effectiveness of the centers. Therefore, an in-depth study of the factors associated with school effectiveness and its relationship with the organization and educational practices will be carried out.},
