abstract = {The gender gap in engineering is a well-known problem that affects the sector across regions and countries, education and professional contexts. In education, the gender gap is not only visible in the number of women who enroll in engineering programs, but also in the percentage of women who finish those studies and finally join the labor market in a job in the engineering sector. Regarding the professional context, the gender gap impacts the solutions and products developed in the different engineering areas. Teams that do not take into account diversity cannot cover the needs of a diverse society. The challenge is not reduced to increase the number of women in engineering areas, but also empower them to solve other gender issues such as the glass ceiling, pay gap or unbalanced sharing of caring responsibilities. For this reason, although we should continue working on increasing the number of women who study engineering, we have also to teach gender equality values to the engineering students as a way to face the inequalities that arise in the labor market. In this context, gender mainstreaming in engineering degrees can have a significant impact. It is important to teach professors to introduce the gender perspective in their lessons. However, a first step is needed to know their opinions and ideas about gender equality in engineering. This work presents the results of a pilot study with engineering educators from different Europe, Middle East, and Africa institutions, which participate in the International Conference EDUCON 2021.},
