abstract = {Abusive use or addiction to the Internet is a reality that is of increasing concern to family members, teachers and researchers. As technology has become established in our society, having a private mobile device with an Internet connection has become standard. This reality has led to an increase in the time of exposure to the Internet access device and thus increased the potential for addiction. The time variable is considered a trigger for addiction and is present in most of the measurement scales. If we add to this reality the social confinement and distance established in our society due to the Covid-19 pandemic, we have the largest increase in time of access to Internet known in history. There are different risk factors for developing an Internet addiction and time is a variable commonly associated with it. Thus, in an era in which reality has changed the time of access to the Internet by the Covid-19 to meet the educational and social demand of adolescents, is there an effective scale to measure addiction that fits the new normality of education in times of Covid-19? This article seeks to answer this question by reviewing the most important scales of Internet addiction in the scientific literature and reflecting on the meaning and use of the time variable as a factor in measuring Internet addiction.},
