abstract = {It is widely demonstrated that academic performance depends on many different factors, and those have a different specific weight depending on the evaluated subject or the academic level.This paper proposes a methodology that includes a mechanism to measure the weight of the variables that really have a direct impact on academic performance. To address this problem, which falls within the scope of prediction, it is appropriate to resort to classification techniques that model academic performance as a discrete variable, even if that variable has a continuous nature.This article presents a methodology based on the hypothesis that the way the performance variable is discretized will significantly affect the predictive models generated. This work highlights a relation between the factorization criteria and the most-relevant attributes selected to classify instances. Also, the paper shows a relation between the predictive model obtained and the target variable factorization criteria.},
