abstract = {The present research aimed to study the relation among body composition by the use of a bioimpediandiometer, training experience and race time in a mountain marathon. Body composition and training pre-race experience analyses were conducted previous to a mountain marathon in 52 male athletes (38.3±10.1 years, 173.9±6.5 cm, 72.7±9.9 kg). A significant correlation of race time in the mountain marathon with age (r=.502; p=.002), fat mass (r=.632; p=.000), percentage of body fat (BF, r=.754; p=.000), level of abdominal obesity (r=.482; p=.005), sport experience (r=.467; p=.007) and daily training volume (r=-.527; p=.002) was shown. In mountain marathon body fat and athlete's age were negatively associated with race performance; by contrary, the volume of daily training was positively associated with mountain marathon performance. A regression analysis showed that race time could be predicted (R2 = 0.948) by daily training load, sports experience, age, fat mass, body fat and level of abdominal obesity. The comparison between performance groups with regards to body composition and training characteristics revealed that the higher performance group was lighter with lower body fat, fat mass and level of abdominal obesity, and with more days of training per week than the lower performance group (p&lt;.05). Therefore, coaches and fitness trainers working with mountain marathon runners should (a) develop exercise and nutritional strategies to reduce body fat, and (b) consider increasing daily training volume as a mean to improve sport performance.},
